ms is 3.\nThe largest number in nums is 8.\nThe greatest common divisor of 3 and 8 is 1.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [3,3]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation:\nThe smallest number in nums is 3.\nThe largest number in nums is 3.\nThe greatest common divisor of 3 and 3 is 3.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n2 <= nums.length <= 1000\n1 <= nums[i] <= 1000\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def findGCD(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\nimport math\n\nclass Solution:\n    def findGCD(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        min_num = min(nums)\n        max_num = max(nums)\n        return math.gcd(min_num, max_num)\n```\n\nThis solution uses Python's built-in `math.gcd` function to find the greatest common divisor of the smallest and largest numbers in the list. The `min` and `max` functions are used to find the smallest and largest numbers in the list, respectively.", "estimated_date": 1629590400000}